<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Official Seeks Cut in EU Trade Restrictions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2302131394 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1225 GMT 23 
Feb 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2302131394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "China Asks For Cut in Trade </F>
Restrictions"] 
  [Text] Beijing, 23 Feb (ANSA) -- Amidst hopes for continued 
trade expansion between European Union [EU] countries and China, 
fears have been expressed about possible effects on China's 
exports from restrictions imposed by The Twelve on Chinese 
products. 
  These fears were mentioned today by Zang Chunzheng, from the 
Chinese Foreign Trade Ministry, with reference to the thirteenth 
meeting between China and the European Union to begin Monday [28 
February] with the participation of Commissioner Leon Brittan. 
  Zang Chunzheng said he hoped the meeting would remove or 
weaken "the quotas and other limitations introduced by the 
Twelve". He described them as "discriminatory measures adopted 
to protect the European market against China". 
  China's re-admission into GATT, the international commerce 
agreement, will be one of the issues examined during Brittan's 
visit. 

</TEXT>

