<F P=101> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Article Views Sino-Japanese Security Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0203124094 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 2 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0203124094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent Toshiichiro Amitani] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, 1 Mar -- Officers in uniform from the 
Self-Defense Forces and the People's Liberation Army held the 
first "Japanese-Chinese Security Talks" at the National Defense 
Ministry [NDM] in Beijing on 1 March. During the talks, 
concerning China's moves to strengthen its military power 
through such measures as the resumption of nuclear testing, 
Japanese officers said: "There are arguments in Asia that 
China's moves might threaten the security of other Asian 
nations. We hope China will boost the transparency in defense 
matters." However, Chinese counterparts reiterated China's 
conventional stand, saying: "Nuclear weapons are solely for 
self-defense. Inflation is the major reason for an increase in 
defense expenditures." 
  At the end of last year, security talks were held between 
officials of the foreign ministries of the two nations. This 
time, uniformed officers held the security dialogue for the 
first time. They included Toshimasa Fujiwara (major general), 
chief of the Joint Staff Council's 5th staff officer section, 
from Japan and Zhan Maohai (major general), deputy director at 
the NDM's Foreign Affairs Bureau, from China. They exchanged 
opinions for about five hours. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

