<F P=101> Military </F>
<H3> <TI>   China To Develop, Build New-Model Jet Fighters </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2901223894 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 28 Jan 
94 Morning Edition p 8 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2901223894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent Katsuhiko Iino] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, 27 Jan -- China has decided to develop and 
build a new-model jet fighter by the end of this century. This 
was disclosed recently by Zhu Yuli, president of the China 
Aircraft Industry Corporation. According to a Chinese military 
source, the new-model jet fighter to be developed has been named 
"Super 7." China is said to plan to use in principle technology 
it has obtained from Soviet-built MiG fighters, but it intends 
to introduce Western state-of-the art technology to develop it. 
The new-model jet fighter will be developed under the "Takeoff 
Plan" the corporation has drawn up as a long-term strategy 
through the end of this century. The plan calls for the 
production of both military and civilian aircraft. According to 
ZHONGGUO HANGKKONG BAO [the China Aviation Newspaper], the plan 
calls for 1) developing China's capability to develop and 
manufacture turbo jet engines for use in military aircraft; 2) 
creating a research and development system to build helicopters 
domestically; 3) aggressively importing loading equipment, 
particularly electronics technology, and 4) developing China's 
capability to design and build a large-type airliner. 
  According to the XINHUA NEWS AGENCY, China built a total of 
256 aircraft in 1993, an increase of 24 percent from a year 
earlier. The production of aircraft engines grew 27 percent 
while the production of missiles increased 53.9 percent. China's 
aircraft trade in the year amounted to approximately $1 billion 
with imports standing at $850 million. The "Takeoff Plan" 
envisions China's aircraft trade at $3 billion in the year 2000. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

