<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports Russia To Help India Modernize Weapons </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0803060994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0531 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0803060994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] New Delhi, March 8 (XINHUA) -- India would get 
Russian help in modernizing its T-72 tanks and other 
Soviet-designed weapons, according to a report reaching here 
today. 
  This was announced by Commander-in-Chief of the Russian land 
Forces Col-Gen Vladimir Semyonov after his final round of talks 
with Indian Army Chief General B.C. Joshi who is paying one-week 
official visit to the country. 
  The Russian general also did not rule out leasing some types 
of weapons for two or three years to India, but he did not 
elaborate. However, observers noted here that India had taken a 
nuclear powered submarine from Russia on lease in the 80s. 
  Report said during his visit to Russia, the Indian army 
chief 
expressed India's willingness to continue military-technical 
cooperation with Russia and said 70 percent of arms with Indian 
Army were Soviet-designed. 
  He also showed interest in purchasing the latest T-72 C 
tanks, self-propelled artillery guns and military aircraft. 
  Joshi was the first Indian Army chief and chairman of the 
Joint Committee of Chiefs of Staff to visit Russia in the last 
four years, according to local sources. 

</TEXT>

