<H3> <TI>   UN Peacekeeping Troops Take Control of Tuzla Airport </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0803024594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0223 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0803024594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, March 7 (XINHUA) -- The first group of the 
UN Protection Force (UNPROFOR) soldiers backed by tanks today 
took control of Tuzla military airport which is expected to be 
opened soon. 
  Some 100 Norwegian soldiers riding in 17 armored personnel 
carriers and six Danish tanks, entered the base to replace 
Bosnia's Muslim troops, who are to officially hand over control 
of the airport at noon Tuesday. 
  Located 15 kilometers from Tuzla city, the airport has been 
the biggest military one in former Yugoslavia with two runways, 
one of which is 2,400 meters long. The airport is capable of 
receiving all types of aircraft. 
  The airport has been closed for more than 10 months. Under 
an accord reached by Bosnian Serb and Russian leaders, the Serbs 
agreed to reopen it on condition of using it only for 
humanitarian purposes. 
  About 300 Swedish soldiers will be deployed there to protect 
the runways. 

</TEXT>

