<H3> <TI>   Croat President Denies Agreement Result of U.S. Aid Offer </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0803052794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0515 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0803052794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, March 7 (XINHUA) -- Croatian President 
Franjo Tudjman insisted today that the Muslim-Croat Federation- 
Confederation Agreement was not a result of instigation by the 
United States and its offer of 500 million U.S. dollars in aid. 
  Tudjman said that Croatia's policy was consistent and that 
its constitution demands a referendum amongst the people to 
finally accept the confederation plan of the accord which was 
signed by Croatia, Bosnia's Croats and Muslims in Washington on 
March 1. 
  Tudjman told a news conference in Zagreb that he and Bosnian 
Muslim leader Alija Izetbegovic had reached agreements, both 
open and secret, on the confederation plan. Izetbegovic had 
repeatedly voiced his support for the Croatian-Muslim alliance, 
he said. 

</TEXT>

