<F P=100> Central Eurasia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Calls For Increased Harmony, Trust, Cooperation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0803031494 Beijing XINHUA in English 0253 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0803031494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, March 7 (XINHUA) -- Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin today appealed to the nation to unite to make Russia 
strong, and called for increased harmony, trust and cooperation. 
  His plea, the second in three days, was made during a 
televised speech marking international working women's day when 
he declared that he will devote himself to these issues. 
  Shortly after his disagreement with the State Duma over its 
amnesty for political rebels, Yeltsin proposed at a cabinet 
meeting held last Friday [4 March] to adopt a memorandum on 
domestic harmony. 
  He said that this was particularly necessary in the present 
situation where the danger of confrontation is looming, 
referring to the release of former Vice-President Aleksandr 
Rutskoy and former parliament Speaker Ruslan Khasbulatov. 
  Observers here noted that a mood of reconciliation and 
cooperation, not seen over the past two years, has been gaining 
ground amongst powerful political forces of the vast Russian 
Federation. 
  In a report to the government, Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin echoed the president's comments made in his state 
of the nation address on February 24. 
  Sergey Glaziyev, chairman of the committee of the economic 
policy of the State Duma, said that the theme of the president's 
address on the state of the nation is consistent with the 
economic policies of the State Duma, or the lower house of 
parliament. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

