<F P=100> West Europe </F>
<H3> <TI>   Netherlands' Foreign Minister To Discuss Human Rights </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK0703141594 Hong Kong AFP in English 1349 GMT 7 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> HK0703141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 7 (AFP) -- Dutch Foreign Minister 
Peter Kooijmans began a round of discussions here on Monday 
looking at China's record on human rights after a wave of 
dissident arrests, Dutch sources said. Kooijmans, a professor 
of international law, is a former UN investigator on human 
rights in China. His first official contacts were with public 
prosecutor Zhang Siqing and Zhu Muzhi, chairman of the China 
Human Rights Society, the Dutch embassy said. Kooijmans is due 
to lunch with Foreign Minister Qian Qichen on Tuesday, and will 
meet Justice Minister Xiao Yang and External Trade Minister Wu 
Yi. 
  His visit came after several dissidents were arrested by 
police as part of a massive operation apparently aimed at 
intimidating opposition groups. According to informed Dutch 
sources, Kooijmans has expressed a wish to visit Wei Jingsheng 
-- China's most famous dissident -- during his stay. Wei was 
interrogated by police for about 30 hours last week and decided 
Sunday to leave Beijing to "rest for a few days", his press 
secretary said. U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher 
arrives in Beijing on Friday for talks with Chinese leaders. 
  Kooijmans' visit will also discuss the planned opening of 
air 
links between Beijing and Amsterdam. Since 1983 the Dutch 
airline KLM has been the only European carrier to fly to Taipei 
daily under its own colours. As a result, China, which regards 
Taiwan as a renegade province, has refused to grant KLM landing 
rights. Other European airlines, like Air France, British 
Airways and Lufthansa, opened routes to Taipei last year, but 
use subsidiary airlines for these operations. 

</TEXT>

