<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mainland Dissidents Leave For Sweden for Political Asylum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0803093994 Taipei CNA in English 0713 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0803093994 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Sofia Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, March 8 (CNA) -- Four Mainland Chinese 
dissidents left Taiwan for Sweden late Monday [7 March] after 
receiving political asylum from the Swedish Government, the 
Chinese Association for Human Rights said Tuesday. 
  Guo Chengdong, Zhang Guozhong, Wang Jingsan and Yin Jin left 
Taiwan more than one year after thy escaped persecution on the 
mainland and sneaked into Taiwan in 1992. "They are the first 
group of mainland dissidents who have been granted political 
asylum by a Western Government after escaping to Taiwan," the 
association said. 
  The four, all in their early 30's, have been wanted by 
mainland authorities for their roles in the student-led 
Tiananmen demonstrations which ended after a bloody crackdown on 
June 4, 1989. 
  They sneaked into Taiwan in September 1992 and were first 
detained at a special reception center in Hsinchu, Northern 
Taiwan along with other illegal mainland immigrants. After 
repeated petitions, they finally convinced the Republic of China 
[ROC] government that they were political dissidents and should 
not be repatriated to the mainland. 
  With the assistance of human rights organizations in Taiwan 
and New York, the four applied for "political refugee" status 
with the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees. The 
Swedish Government recently agreed to accept the four as 
"political refugees." 
  The ROC Government gave each of them US$1,000 pocket money 
and other gifts before their departure. The government will 
also provide them with one-year grants for Swedish language 
study and other living expenses. 
  Taiwan is reluctant to let them stay in consideration of 
relations with the mainland, some observers said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

