<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Lift Japanese Film Quotas in GATT Effort </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0803101794 Taipei CNA in English 0655 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0803101794 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Danielle Yang] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, March 8 (CNA) -- The Government 
Information Office (GIO) has decided to lift restrictions on the 
import of Japanese films to help Taiwan's bid to enter the 
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT). 
  GIO officials made the decision during a Monday [7 March] 
meeting presided over by GIO Deputy Director-General Charles C. 
L. Wu. 
  The GIO prohibited the import of Japanese films in 1973, one 
year after diplomatic ties between the Republic of China [ROC] 
and Japan were severed. 
  But since 1984, the GIO has allowed limited imports under a 
quota system. The current quota system will expire on September 
30 at which time all import restrictions are expected to be 
lifted. 
  The elimination of restrictions on imported Japanese films 
will have a favorable impact on Taiwan's bid for full GATT 
membership, the GIO noted. 
  Participants at the Monday meeting included representatives 
from the Foreign Ministry, Education Ministry, Board of Foreign 
Trade, and movie industry. 

</TEXT>

