<F P=100> TAIWAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cross-Strait Trade Growth Slows in 1993 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0503152594 Taipei CNA in English 1305 GMT 5 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0503152594 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Danielle Yang] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, March 5 (CNA) -- Cross-strait trade in 1993 
reached U.S.$13.831 billion, according to statistics released by 
the Board of Foreign Trade (BOFT) Saturday. 
  Exports to Mainland China totaled U.S.$12.728 billion while 
imports from the mainland totaled U.S.$1.103 billion, the 
statistics showed. 
  Hong Kong customs tallies, however, showed cross-strait 
trade 
last year totaled only U.S.$8.689 billion, up 17.31 percent from 
a year earlier. They showed Taiwan exports to the mainland 
growing 20.63 percent to U.S.$7.585 billion, and its imports 
from the mainland growing 1.38 percent to U.S.$1.104 billion. 
  Whichever statistics are used, they indicate that the 
mainland fever of a few years ago has slowed, a BOFT official 
said, noting that the annual growth rate of exports to the 
mainland a few years ago was above 40 percent. 
  The BOFT and Hong Kong customs figures are different, the 
official said, because Hong Kong only counts Taiwan exports that 
pass through customs checks, and not the ones that are simply in 
transit to the mainland. 

</TEXT>

